Minor Flood Warning for the King River at Docker Road

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOCKER RD BRIDGE.

Moderate rainfall has been observed since Friday night in the Ovens and King catchments which has caused river level rises. Minor flooding is occurring along the King River at Docker Road Bridge, where river levels are now falling. Further downstream along the Ovens River, a peak near the minor flood level is possible at Wangaratta overnight Tuesday into Wednesday. 

Showery conditions are expected to continue for the next few days but forecast rainfall totals are not expected to significantly affect river levels. 

King River: 

Minor flooding is occurring at Docker Rd Bridge. 

No current observations are available for the King River at Lake William Hovell (Downstream), however the river level is expected to be below the minor flood level and falling. The King River at Lake William Hovell (Downstream) is likely to remain below the minor flood level (1.80 m). 

The King River at Docker Rd Bridge peaked near 3.89 m Monday afternoon, with minor flooding. The river is currently at 3.81 m and falling slowly, with minor flooding. The King River at Docker Rd Bridge may fall below the minor flood level (3.70 m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday. 
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • Low lying agricultural farmland may be flooded.
  • Floodwater may impact Docker-Carboor Road between Wangaratta and Whitfield Road, and Oxley to Meadow Creek Road
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/07/2025 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact the National Relay Service and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
Minor Flood Warning for the Kiewa River

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT BANDIANA AND POSSIBLE AT KIEWA TUESDAY AFTERNOON 

Moderate to heavy rainfall in the Kiewa catchment over the last few days has resulted in minor flooding along the lower Kiewa River at Bandiana. Further upstream, river level rises are occurring at Kiewa, where minor flooding is possible. 

Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge: 

Minor flooding is occurring along the Kiewa River at Bandiana and is possible at Kiewa. 

The Kiewa River Channel at Kiewa is currently at 3.19 m and rising slowly, below the minor flood level. The Kiewa River Channel at Kiewa may peak near the minor flood level (3.30 m) Tuesday afternoon. 

The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 2.84 m and steady, with minor flooding. The Kiewa River at Bandiana may remain around the minor flood level (2.80 m) until Wednesday afternoon
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  •  Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/07/2025 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app

  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact the National Relay Service and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT WANGARATTA OVERNIGHT TUESDAY INTO WEDNESDAY 

Moderate rainfall has been observed since Friday night in the Ovens and King catchments which has caused river level rises. Minor flooding is occurring along the King River at Docker Road Bridge, where river levels are now falling. Further downstream along the Ovens River, a peak near the minor flood level is possible at Wangaratta overnight Tuesday into Wednesday. 

Showery conditions are expected to continue for the next few days but forecast rainfall totals are not expected to significantly affect river levels.

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point: 

Minor flooding is possible along the Ovens River at Wangaratta. The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 11.48 m and rising slowly, below the minor flood level. The Ovens River at Wangaratta may reach around the minor flood level (11.90 m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday. 
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • If the Ovens river reaches the minor flood level of 11.9 meters, APEX Park and farmland along the Ovens and King floodplains to the  north, south and east of Wangaratta may begin flooding. 
  • Bike paths and walking tracks may be closed at 11.6 meters around APEX Park, the Northern Beaches.
  • Riverside carparks may be closed before flooding, including Sydney Beach, Bickerton Streets and Baker Streets.  
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/07/2025 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.
